Gambia, as a signatory to the CEDAW Convention, has a duty to guarantee women their right to make fully-informed choices in relation to reproductive health, encompassing the right to access all information on vulnerable groups such as adolescents. Currently, abortion is not discussed by the media or in the curriculum at schools. There is a lot of stigma attached to discussing abortions, thus making information on the subject hard to access.
The criminalization of abortion in Gambia has led some women to seek abortions, sometimes from quasi-medical personnel, risking their reproductive health as a result. During a study in 1993, over half the women undergoing an abortion suffered paralysis and many others died, due to faulty procedures from quacks and witch doctors. Some women admitted to miscarrying several times, as it would lessen the stigma and suspicion attached to any abortion procedures.
Public Health

Why do women seek abortions?

Most women seek abortions due to social and economic reasons, such as poverty, domestic violence, conflict or pre-marital sex. In a country where most couples don’t use contraceptives, fifteen percent of pregnancies end in abortion.
